Anonymous Sat 15 May 2021 21:39:05 No.38702656 Report

>>38702373
Pretty wrong actually. Firearms were seldom used in the 1400s due to inferior and unstable production of vlackpowder as well as lack of standardization for artillery in the form of carriages and balls. Come the late 1400s France's Charles the viiith introduced standardized cannons into the wider French military and with success destroyed several fortified Italian cities resulting in their immediate surrender. Firearms came soon to replace crossbows, as before they were used in tandem to strengthen one another but now in the 1500s the aquebus replaced the crossbow due to improved blackpowder and ease in training.
China and Korea would maintain firearms but not to the quality of Europe, prefering to use them tandem with bows due to the ming and qing dynasties ties to steppe tribes. Due to the new world and improved ocean sailing strategies and technologies the silk road would die and result in 1500s and 1600s China not getting European firearm improvements for some time.
So gunpowder would be well known and widely used but not act as a replacement for past weapons in China, more like a new tool for armies.
